<BaseLayout title="Act Three" active="guide" description="Macbeth Act Three guide: the murder of Banquo, the banquet and the ghost, and the tyrant's isolation, with scene summaries, analysis of form and structure, and verified quotations for the coursework.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">The Guide &middot; Act Three</p>
      <h1>The tyrant closes the door</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        The crown is won and immediately worthless. Act Three is the act of a man who cannot
        stop: he murders his friend to secure a throne he already holds, then watches the dead
        walk back into his own hall. This is where ambition curdles into tyranny, and where
        Macbeth begins to rule alone.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">What happens</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 1 (the royal palace at Forres).</strong> Banquo, now the only man who
        heard the witches and who suspects how Macbeth came by the crown, keeps his thoughts
        to himself while accepting an invitation to that night&rsquo;s feast. Left alone,
        Macbeth turns the prophecy over: the sisters hailed Banquo as father to kings, so
        Macbeth has murdered Duncan only to hand the succession to another man&rsquo;s line. He
        summons two hired murderers, works on their grievances, and sets them to kill Banquo
        and his son Fleance on the road home.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 2 (the palace).</strong> Macbeth and his wife circle each other, both
        sleepless and afraid, neither quite reaching the other. She counsels him to look
        cheerful before the guests; he broods that they have wounded the danger without
        destroying it. For the first time he keeps his plan from her, promising a deed she will
        applaud once it is done, and telling her only to stay innocent of it for now.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 3 (a park near the palace).</strong> The murderers, joined by a
        mysterious third, ambush Banquo in the dark. They kill him, but in the confusion
        Fleance escapes, which is the outcome Macbeth most feared: the father is dead, the line
        survives.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 4 (the banqueting hall).</strong> At the feast that should crown his
        reign, Macbeth learns that Fleance is loose, then sees Banquo&rsquo;s ghost take his
        place at the table. He rages at a figure only he can see while his wife struggles to
        hold the room together, explaining away his fit as an old affliction. The ghost returns,
        Macbeth breaks down entirely, and Lady Macbeth is forced to send the horrified lords
        away. Alone again, Macbeth resolves to visit the witches and notes that Macduff has
        refused to attend.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 5 (a heath).</strong> Hecate, goddess of witchcraft, scolds the sisters
        for meddling with Macbeth without her, and promises spells that will lull him into false
        security. Many editors doubt Shakespeare wrote this scene; it reads as a later addition
        of spectacle, and its neat rhymes sit oddly beside the rest of the act.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 6 (elsewhere in Scotland).</strong> Lennox and another lord speak with
        heavy irony about recent deaths, testing each other before saying what they mean:
        Scotland is suffering under a tyrant, Macduff has fled to England to join Duncan&rsquo;s
        son Malcolm, and men are beginning to hope for an army that will free the country.
      </p>

      <h2>A closer look</h2>
      <h3>The murder of Banquo, and the loneliness of the throne</h3>
      <p>
        Macbeth kills Duncan with his wife at his shoulder; he kills Banquo alone. That change
        of company is the real subject of the act. In a play written for a king who traced his
        house to Banquo, the historical Banquo had to be cleaned up into a figure of loyal
        restraint, and Shakespeare uses that restraint against Macbeth: Banquo is the man
        Macbeth might have been, tempted by the same prophecy and choosing to wait on
        providence rather than force it. So the soliloquy that opens the act, &lsquo;To be thus
        is nothing, but to be safely thus&rsquo;, is not the language of a triumphant king but
        of a frightened one. The crown, once the summit of ambition, has become merely a
        position to be defended, and the defence has no end. When Macbeth admits &lsquo;There is
        none but he whose being I do fear&rsquo;, he is confessing that his security now depends
        on the death of the one honest man left near him. Tyranny, the act argues, is not power
        enjoyed but power endlessly, exhaustingly guarded.
      </p>
      <h3>The banquet: the private crime made public</h3>
      <p>
        The banquet in Scene 4 is the hinge of the whole play, and its power is a matter of
        staging. A feast is the image of a well-ordered kingdom: the king seated among his
        thanes, degree observed, hospitality honoured. Shakespeare builds that image only to
        shatter it. Banquo&rsquo;s ghost, visible to Macbeth and to us but not to the guests,
        turns the public ceremony into a private hell played out in front of witnesses. The
        horror is dramatic irony made physical: the audience sees exactly what the court cannot,
        and watches the king incriminate himself in gasps and half-sentences. Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s
        frantic management, &lsquo;you have displaced the mirth&rsquo;,
        shows the partnership beginning to fail, because there is now something she cannot
        smooth over. When Macbeth says &lsquo;It will have blood, they say. Blood will have
        blood&rsquo;, he states the moral law of the tragedy: murder is not an event that ends
        but a debt that compounds. The banquet is the moment the whole court begins to
        understand what kind of man now rules them.
      </p>
      <h3>Form and structure: the quickening slide</h3>
      <p>
        Structurally, Act Three is built to feel faster and darker than what came before.
        Where Act One and Act Two lingered on hesitation, weighing a single deed across long
        soliloquies, Act Three moves in short, brutal steps: a decision, a hiring, an ambush, a
        collapse. Macbeth&rsquo;s own imagery marks the change. Earlier he agonised; now he
        speaks of being &lsquo;in blood stepped in so far&rsquo; that turning back is as hard as
        going on, converting murder from a moral choice into a kind of momentum. The tell-tale
        structural shift is that he stops confiding in his wife. &lsquo;We have scorched the
        snake, not killed it&rsquo; is spoken to her; the plan against Banquo is kept from her.
        That withheld secret is the crack in the marriage that Act Five will widen into a chasm.
        Even the placing of the Hecate scene, whether Shakespeare&rsquo;s or not, serves the
        design: after the ghost, the play pulls back to the supernatural machinery, reminding us
        that Macbeth is being drawn on toward the apparitions of Act Four. The act ends not with
        Macbeth but with Lennox and a lord, the first scene to look at the tyrant from outside,
        and the first hint that the country will rise.
      </p>

      <h2>Key quotations</h2>
      <table class="quote-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Quotation</th><th>Method</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;To be thus is nothing, but to be safely thus&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Antithesis, soliloquy</td>
            <td>The crown is redefined as a thing to guard, not enjoy. Ambition has become fear, and the tyrant&rsquo;s isolation begins in his own mind.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;There is none but he whose being I do fear&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Hyperbole, confession</td>
            <td>Macbeth&rsquo;s safety now rests on killing the last honest man near him. Banquo is condemned precisely because he is good.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;We have scorched the snake, not killed it&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor</td>
            <td>The wound imagined as a living threat: the crime is not finished but festering, and will demand more blood to contain it.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;O, full of scorpions is my mind, dear wife&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor, direct address</td>
            <td>Guilt rendered as physical torment. The tenderness of &lsquo;dear wife&rsquo; sits beside a mind he can no longer share with her.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;It will have blood, they say. Blood will have blood&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 4)</td>
            <td class="m">Repetition, proverb</td>
            <td>States the tragedy&rsquo;s moral law: murder compounds. The folk saying gives cosmic authority to a private terror.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;You have displaced the mirth&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 4)</td>
            <td class="m">Public rebuke, imagery of order</td>
            <td>Lady Macbeth fighting to hold the ceremony together. The broken feast images a broken kingdom, and a partnership starting to fail.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;I am in blood stepped in so far&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 4)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor of wading</td>
            <td>Murder reframed as momentum, not choice: going back seems as hard as going on. The tragic hero forfeits his last exit.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;The time has been that, when the brains were out, the man would die&rsquo; (Act 3, Scene 4)</td>
            <td class="m">Dramatic irony, the uncanny</td>
            <td>The natural order itself seems overturned: the dead will not stay dead. Macbeth&rsquo;s crime has disordered the world he wanted to command.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="box think">
        <h3>Think it through</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Why does Shakespeare have Macbeth murder Banquo without telling his wife? What does that single withheld secret do to their marriage?</li>
          <li>The ghost is visible to Macbeth and the audience but not to the guests. How would the scene change if the ghost were left off stage entirely, a thing only described?</li>
          <li>Fleance&rsquo;s escape ruins Macbeth&rsquo;s plan. Why might Shakespeare want the audience, watching under King James, to feel relief rather than suspense there?</li>
          <li>Is Macbeth still a tragic hero in this act, or has he become simply a tyrant? Where would you place the line, and why?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="box exam">
        <h3>Towards the coursework</h3>
        <p>
          Act Three feeds all three set questions. For <strong>kingship</strong>, contrast the
          feast, an emblem of ordered rule, with the tyrant who wrecks it: this is what bad
          kingship looks like from the inside. For the <strong>presentation of women</strong>,
          track Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s shift from instigator to damage-controller: she manages the
          banquet but is no longer trusted with the plan, and her power is visibly shrinking.
          For <strong>masculinity</strong>, notice how Macbeth proves his manhood now through
          hired killing and public bravado rather than the battlefield courage of Act One.
          <strong>Writing task:</strong> in one paragraph, argue whether the banquet scene shows
          Macbeth losing control or Lady Macbeth losing control, opening with a contextual angle
          (the feast as a model of the ordered kingdom) and looping back to it in your analysis.
          Take your working method to the <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

